 which is from either Old Norse <i>kartr</i> or Old English <i>cræt</i>, both of which, like the Late Latin word, were probably derived from Celtic. This surname is also very common among African Americans.","Irish: shortened form of   McCarter  .","Americanized form of German   Karter   ‘carder’."],"variants":[{"name":"Charman","meanings":["English (Sussex and Surrey): occupational name for a carter, carrier, or coachman, from Middle English (Old French) <i>char</i>, <i>car</i> ‘car, cart, carriage’ + Middle English <i>man</i> ‘man’. Compare   Carter   and   Carman   2.","English (Sussex and Surrey): occupational name for someone who did odd jobs, from Middle English <i>char(re)</i>, <i>chere</i> (Old English <i>cier(r)</i>, <i>cer(r)</i>, <i>cear(r)</i>, <i>cær(r)</i>) ‘turn (of activity), small job, chore’ + <i>man</i>. Compare   Carman   2.","In some cases probably also an Americanized form of Slovenian <b>Čarman</b> (see   Carman   5)."]},{"name":"Chartier","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Armand, Normand, Jacques, Marcel, Adelard, Alcide, Emile, Gilles, Raoul, Rosaire, Alphonse.","French: shortened form of <i>charretier</i>, an occupational name for a carter, from an agent derivative of Old French <i>charette</i> ‘cart’.","French Canadian: altered form of English   Carter  , a cognate of 1 above. Compare   Sharkey   and   Shorkey  ."]},{"name":"Karter","meanings":["German: occupational name for a carder (someone who prepares wool for spinning), from Middle High German <i>karter</i>. Compare   Carter  ."]},{"name":"McCarter","meanings":["Scottish and northern Irish: variant of   McArthur  ."]},{"name":"Carrier","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Andre, Marcel, Emile, Lucien, Cecile, Alain, Gaetan, Gilles, Jacques, Laurent, Normand.","English and southern French: from Middle English, Old French <i>car(r)ier</i> (from Late Latin <i>carrarius</i>, a derivative of <i>carrum</i> ‘cart, wagon’, a word of Gaulish origin), an occupational name for a carter (see   Carter  ), in French also for a cartwright. Compare French   Charrier  .","French: occupational name for a stonemason or quarryman, <i>carrier</i>. Compare   Coyer  ."]},{"name":"Cartman","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Lancashire): occupational name from Middle English <i>cartman</i> ‘man who operated a cart for the transport of goods’. Compare   Carter  .","Americanized form of German <b>Kartmann</b> (see   Kartman  )."]}]},{"name":"Silvester","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Latin name, meaning ‘of the woods’. It was borne by various early saints, most notably by the first pope to govern a Church free from persecution (  314–35 ). His feast is on  31 December , and in various parts of Europe the New Year is celebrated under his name. The name has been continuously, if modestly, used from the Middle Ages to the present day."],"variants":[{"name":"Sylvester","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Silvester ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Silvester Carter was born in England, United Kingdom. He married Mrs Silvester Carter before 1425, in Wrotham, Kent, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"–":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1425–Female":"1425–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","before 1425":"enne 1425","1425":"1425","Wrotham, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Wrotham, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Wrotham, Kent, England":"Wrotham, Kent, England","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"–":"Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1425–Female":"1425–Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","before 1425":"ennen vuotta 1425","1425":"1425","Wrotham, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Wrotham, Kent, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Wrotham, Kent, England":"Wrotham, Kent, England","England, United Kingdom":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"–":"Décédé","–Female":"Décédée","1425–Female":"1425–Décédée","–Male":"Décédé","